New York brought action seeking a judgment declaring that during the preceding ten years specified counties did not use State\rquote s voting qualifications \u8216\'3ffor the purpose or with the effect of denying or abridging the right to vote on account of race or color\u8217\'3f and that Voting Rights Act sections designed to prohibit use of test or device for the alteration of voting qualifications or procedures when purpose or effect is to deprive a citizen of his right to vote were thus inapplicable to such counties. Three-Judge District Court for the District of Columbia denied a motion to intervene and granted summary judgment for New York, and unsuccessful intervenors appealed. The Supreme Court, Mr. Justice Blackmun, held that the words \u8216\'3fany appeal,\u8217\'3f within Voting Rights Act section relating to action by State or political subdivision for declaratory judgment as to absence of denial or abridgment of voting rights on account of race or color and providing that action shall be heard and determined by a court of three judges and appeal shall lie to the Supreme Court, encompass appeal by a would-be, but unsuccessful, intervenor, but that the subject motion to intervene was untimely, and the District Court, did not, in light of such fact and other circumstances of case, abuse its discretion in denying the motion.
